I find myself doing this a lot with `Regex`es:

```csharp
// Some example regex. Don't judge me!!
var myRegex = new Regex(@"^https?://(www\.)?github.com/(?<owner>[^/]+)/(?<repo>[^/]+)/?.*$");

var match = myRegex.Match(inputString);
if (match.Success)
{
    var owner = match.Groups["owner"].Value;
    // ... work with the match
}
else
{
    // Do something else
}
```

I think this could be made a little more ergonomic through a new method on Regex, TryMatch. With such a method, this code could become:

```csharp
// Some example regex. Don't judge me!!
var myRegex = new Regex(@"^https?://(www\.)?github.com/(?<owner>[^/]+)/(?<repo>[^/]+)/?.*$");

if (myRegex.TryMatch(inputString, out var match))
{
    var owner = match.Groups["owner"].Value;
    // ... work with the match
}
else
{
    // Do something else
}
```

Yes, it's only a small change (one line), but it feels more _ergonomic_ to me. Before `out var` support in C#, this would've been just as clumsy as the current model, but now that we have `out var` this syntax feels like a valuable and simple addition.

I get that "ergonomics" and "aesthetics" are subjective measures though, so would welcome other input here.

## Proposed API

```csharp
public class Regex
{
	// Copied from the overloads of Match.
	public bool TryMatch(string input, out Match match);
	public bool TryMatch(string input, int startat, out Match match);
	public bool TryMatch(string input, int beginning, int length, out Match match);

	// Since the static Match methods already exist, adding a static TryMatch would be consistent. They have different args though.
	// I feel less strongly about these since I avoid the static methods on Regex.
	public static bool TryMatch(string input, string pattern, out Match match);
	public static bool TryMatch(string input, string pattern, RegexOptions options, out Match match);
	public static bool TryMatch(string input, string pattern, RegexOptions options, TimeSpan matchTimeout, out Match match);
}
```

## Implementation

It's trivial to implement this, here's an example set of extension methods I use:

```csharp
public static class RegexExtensions
{
    public static bool TryMatch(this Regex regex, string input, out Match match)
    {
        match = regex.Match(input);
        return match.Success;
    }

    public static bool TryMatch(this Regex regex, string input, int startat, out Match match)
    {
        match = regex.Match(input, startat);
        return match.Success;
    }

    public static bool TryMatch(this Regex regex, string input, int beginning, int length, out Match match)
    {
        match = regex.Match(input, beginning, length);
        return match.Success;
    }
}
```

Note that in this implementation, the value of `match` is *valid* in both branches of an `if(TryMatch(...)) {} else {}` because the match object is always returned, even in the case of an unsuccessful match. I'm certainly open to having a discussion on that. I don't feel strongly either way.

In the end, I have my extension methods so I can do just fine with those, but I think this could be useful and more discoverable if it was in the BCL.

I'd be willing to submit a PR if this was approved for consideration.

